Hi Lynn. I understand the confusion, so let me clarify so we can keep things moving smoothly.

There are two ways an Attorney-in-Fact document can be notarized in North Carolina:

The principal signs in front of a notary.

The attorney-in-fact acknowledges the signature and authority before a notary.

Both are fully valid under North Carolina law.

In this case, our designated AIF completed the notary acknowledgment on their end, which is why the document is notarized and acceptable for closing. This does not require you to personally sit with a notary \u2014 the law allows the attorney-in-fact to handle that portion.

Your signature is what grants the authority, and the notary acknowledgment is what makes it recordable.

Everything is compliant and your closing is fully on track.

My only goal is to make sure you receive your funds without any delays.
